The tomb faces [[:en:Mount Miwa|Mount Miwa]], a sacred mountain.<ref name="Ishino-1992a" /> The [[Kojiki]], says the god [[Ōmononushi]] wanted people to worship him on this mountain.<ref name="Ishino-1992a" /> There is a complex narrative about [[:en:Emperor Sujin|Emperor Sujin]] and the establishment of worship in the region.<ref name="Ellwood-1990a">{{Cite journal |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217 |jstor=30234018 |issn=0304-1042|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name="Hardacre-2017a">{{Cite book |last=Hardacre |first=Helen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Q81DQAAQBAJ |title=Shinto: A History |date=2017 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-062171-1 |language=en}}</ref>{{rp|22}} with some interpreting the god as being [[Yamato Okunitama|Yamato-no-Okunitama]] one of the two gods previously worshipped in the Imperial palace alongside [[Amaterasu]].<ref name="Ellwood-1990a" /><ref name="Hardacre-2017a" />{{rp|22}} The tomb's direction shows that the Makimuku area's rulers and people respected [[:en:Mount Miwa|Mount Miwa]] deeply. Buildings at the Makimuku site also face [[:en:Mount Miwa|Mount Miwa]] on purpose. This shows their [[:en:Mountain worship|religious link]] to the mountain.<ref name="Ishino-1992a" />
